### Setup

Before merging this PR, the CI providers need to be provided access to the repository.

**Travis CI**        

From [Travis CI](https://github.com/marketplace/travis-ci) on Github Marketplace, select the Open Source Plan and proceed with the installation. Fill in the details to proceed to complete the nil payment and authorize Travis. Travis recommends granting access to all repositories on the account, however that is entirely optional and does not impact the service in any way. Grant Travis CI access to this repository.

Now, proceed to [Travis CI Organisation website](https://travis-ci.org/).  Note that Travis has two separate domains, the .org domain is for projects on open Source Plan whereas the .com domain is for all other plan. _Question from Chap: is this still the case? Did [this announcement in 2018][travcom] change any of that? If I read it correctly, the GitHub Apps integration it refers to might be preferable from a permission perspective._ From the Travis website, Sign In with Github and activate Travis for the repository from the dashboard. This completes the Travis CI setup.

**AppVeyor**       
 
From the Github Marketplace, install [AppVeyor](https://github.com/marketplace/appveyor) with the Open Source Plan. The process is similar till AppVeyor has been granted authorization. Sign in on the [AppVeyor website](https://ci.appveyor.com/) with the Github account.

Create a new project and grant AppVeyor access to this repository using either of the two options as it seems fit. Click add next to this repository. This should be enough to setup AppVeyor.

### Debug Builds

Often, it might be desirable to SSH directly into a build environment directly and experiment or debug an issue. 

**Travis CI**

Travis activates debug builds for public repositories only when requested to do so. The procedure is straightforward. An email should be written to support@travis-ci.com from the associated account with the details of this repository. Even the URL is enough. This is a one time process. Once activated, the support will reach out with detailed instructions to launch a debug build. The instructions are listed here again for the sake of completeness.

* Obtain the authentication token from [Travis Account Preferences](https://travis-ci.org/account/preferences).
* Obtain the Job ID of the specific build job desired. The Job ID is the last part of the URL of the build log. For instance, 378505092 is the Job ID in https://travis-ci.com/github/amCap1712/pljava/jobs/378505092.
* Send a POST request to https://api.travis-ci.org/job/${id}/debug with authentication token, Job ID and the headers as in the following example.
```bash
curl -s -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Accept: application/json" \
  -H "Travis-API-Version: 3" \
  -H "Authorization: token ${token}" \
  -d "{\"quiet\": true}" \
  https://api.travis-ci.org/job/${id}/debug
```
* Open the URL of the build log. Travis will perform some initial steps like cloning the repository and installing JDK. After that, it'll display a link of the form `ssh N44GWZCpUxBZKeETeM47D8KaE@nyc1.tmate.io`. This link can be used to SSH into the virtual machine interactive environment.     

*Notes*
Travis installs the correct JDK as associated with the job but does not set the `JAVA_HOME` in debug builds. So, this should be manually set to the correct value. Also, once in the virtual environment, there are a bunch of useful commands like `travis_run_before_install`, `travis_run_script` and so on which will execute the commands in the phase as declared in the `travis.yml` file.

*Precautions*
The SSH link is visible publicly and can be used by anyone to log into the virtual environment while it is active. Therefore, care should be taken to not expose any environment secrets during debugging. Also, the debug logs will visible publicly. Though, they can be deleted later.

Refer to https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/running-build-in-debug-mode/ for complete documentation.

**AppVeyor**

Unlike Travis, AppVeyor does not need any special configuration to enable debug builds. The following line should be added to `.appveyor.yml` file.

```
- ps: $blockRdp = $true; iex ((new-object net.webclient).DownloadString('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/appveyor/ci/master/scripts/enable-rdp.ps1'))
```

AppVeyor will execute all commands till the above line is encountered at which point it will halt and display the IP address and the username to launch a Remote Desktop into the virtual environment. The password to be used is specified by `APPVEYOR_RDP_PASSWORD` in the .appveyor.yml.

*Notes*

Any commands that modify environment variables or configure the environment in some way should be executed again as needed once inside the virtual environment.

For enhanced security, instead of specifying the `APPVEYOR_RDP_PASSWORD` in the `.appveyor.yml`, it can be defined in the environment variables from the settings of the repository on AppVeyor website.

Refer to https://www.appveyor.com/docs/how-to/rdp-to-build-worker/ for complete documentation.

[travcom]: https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/migrate/open-source-on-travis-ci-com/

pr_body:
The PL/Java PGXS Maven plugin is aimed at replacing the combination of `nar-maven-plugin` and bits of script run via the `maven-antrun-plugin` that has been used until now for building the native C code in PL/Java. It will allow the build logic to be expressed in script snippets directly in the POM file, supported by Java-implemented functions for key building-block operations.

It also allows scripting to define Maven reports, which formerly could not be done even with the `maven-antrun-plugin` workaround, as that plugin was not active in the site reporting lifecycle. The initial use is to replace the `maven-javadoc-plugin`, which had proven inadequate to the task of generating PL/Java's javadoc.

The Java part of this plugin is largely ready and contained in this PR, which also uses the scripted-report ability and has replaced the `maven-javadoc-plugin`.

Remaining work on this plugin, to complete the native-code-building and replace the uses of `nar-maven-plugin` and `maven-antrun-plugin`, will be addressed in a future PR.

pr_title: Integrate PL/Java PGXS plugin in pljava-so build process
pr_body:
The PR improves on the PL/Java PGXS plugin introduced in an earlier PR. nar-maven-plugin is now completely removed from the build process. The pljava-so artifact is instead built using the ScriptingMojo and leveraging the JavaScripting capabilities it exposes.

Supersedes #291
